<TITLE>Sad letdown for chess kids</TITLE>
<TEXT>
2 Views 0 Comment African Championship Chess SA Eastern Cape Schools Chess Fungile Ngceka Nomfusi Vusa World Individual Championship Chess player Hlomisa Vusa is among one of several from the Eastern Cape who were not invited to an open tournament in Zambia Picture Brian Witbooi No tournament invitations despite qualifying Angry parents are blaming the Eastern Cape schools chess structure after their children who qualified did not receive an invitation to an open tournament that took place in Zambia last month The parents whose children were not able to attend either the African Championship in Zambia or the World Individual Championship in Russia claimed a lack of communication was the biggest problem The young qualifying players had a choice between the two events with costs being the most differentiating factor and the African tournament being the less expensive It is not known exactly how many children who wished to attend but did not receive invitations from the national chess body were affected because the national body relies on the regions to supply names However parent Nomfusi Vusa 45 of Bridgemeade said she had been prepared to pay for her 15 year old daughter Hlomisa to attend the event in Zambia but the problem was a lack of communication We did not receive any indication since Hlomisa won in the U15 division last year what the way forward would be she said When she attended the South African Winter Schools Chess Championship tournament in Durban they went as a union and because of that I never thought it was my responsibility to follow up It is frustrating because it was a glorious time after she qualified She even received braiding on her school blazer because of this and then she was unable to attend the tournament in Zambia Vusa said She added that her daughter had spent most of her time preparing for the Zambia tournament but ended up attending the local championship in Boksburg instead Nicole Peter 34 of Humewood whose sons Neathan 9 and Noah 7 qualified because they were among the top 22 players in the country said they had not received invitations either There are huge communication gaps in the Eastern Cape Peter said 
